node.text: Thanks for catching up @uptin - chatting about the pandemic and how the economic damage and mental health damage from this is not being proportionately viewed relative to the virus alone. Everyone has an opinion, without necessarily backing it up with the knowledge - my knowledge comes from the economic and statistical side (few of us are virologists and epidemiologists), and the economic damage also results in deaths and lower living standards and poverty lines get breached. Think about this from a wider perspective than simply economy is stock markets (which it categorically isn’t). #pandemic

node.text: This is in no way investment advice, just my personal opinion. I’ve been asked by a lot of people on my thoughts going into the most divisive election ever as an ex-trader/investment banker. My answer: volatility. The health of the US economy is awful. Delinquencies are at 2008 levels and will really hit next year, and stock indices trade at p/e multiple levels never seen before. Regardless, the market seems to have priced in a Biden victory, without forgetting that whatever the result, Trump will still be in office until (at least) January 20,2021. That means one thing: volatility. Now the VIX index is one that even most traders don’t understand, even more so the VILX which looks at short term Vol on call and put contracts traded on the S&P. Volatility is already elevated, which means future volatility could bring the index back down. But from this starting point, any turmoil, and contested votes, and the reality that right after the election, the US faces a December 11 government shutdown deadline again, with people already really struggling and short of cash, means that the unpredictable could be the best way to trade the market. Long, short, small gains, cool. Volatility is the best bet in my personal opinion. #election2020 #election #elections2020 #bidenharris2020 #trump2020 #stockmarkets #investmentbanker

node.text:
Tired of seeing headlines about how stock markets are at all time highs? Struggling personally like almost everyone? Coming from an ex-investment banker and economist, the economy is a complete mess. The divide between Wall Street and Main Street (the real everyday economy for you and I) has never been so big. Some shocking facts here about the amount of money printed into the system:

22% of every USD EVER MADE, was printed THIS YEAR. That leads to inflation. Have you felt the positive effects of this money printing personally? Didn’t think so. 

I just look at the mechanics here and keep politics out of the discussion, but have millennials and young people just been forced into “Generation Nothing?” - millennials are 72 million people in the US workforce, but own just 5% of the wealth. More money was printed in June this year than the first 200 years of the Federal Reserve’s existence. 

This is not sustainable.

#economy #finance #wallstreet

node.text: Another one of my Lil’ economic rants from an ex-investment banker. It’s pretty shocking for me to see the huge gap between Wall Street and Main Street and it makes me furious to be honest. Widespread government stimulus like never seen before and low interest rates have meant that equity prices (and company valuations have reached all time highs (particularly on a P/E basis (price to earnings)). However, the pain real everyday people are feeling, losing jobs and income doesn’t reflect the gains in stocks. It’s difficult out there, really difficult, and the stock markets don’t accurately reflect reality. With that, companies are seemingly ‘fighting for survival’ whilst actually many are using these times as an excuse to reorganise. As airlines have. Firing so many staff, whilst receiving record bailout packages. Who are the winners? Shareholders. Greed always does, and always will come back to bite the stock market. Stay tuned. It’s about the pain everyday people feel right now is felt where it matters, so that policy can be realistic to help Main Street, NOT Wall Street.

People are quick to make judgments without understanding the full situation and it’s pathetic. If you’re guilty of this, then please stop being an asshole. As long as people are not expressing racist, xenophobic, homophobic, violence encouraging videos etc (or pro- @iberia of course, that’s a joke people!!!!), then let them be and understand why people HAVE a different opinion. Let them have it and understand why people have different opinions. It’s how we learn and grow, rather than social media in 2020 being so many people trying to impose their opinions on others as if they are facts. Not everyone posts everything (or every good deed they do on social media). As an example from first hand experience when I went to Yemen, it’s never going to be ‘right’ or ‘enough’ for some people. Do more, give more, say more, said from the comfort of their homes behind a screen. When did we forget to be empathetic and importantly, smart about discussion. node.text: Another in my finance series (rants) - Why is no one talking about Thomas cook and the 20,000 job losses, as the company reforms quietly this year to re-start operations. Many of you know I used to be a trader in banking and I traded CDS (credit default swaps) - a ‘dirty’ word from the 2008-11 financial crisis. So what really happened with Thomas Cook? The media (who mostly don’t understand CDS, which many don’t and is fair enough), say that Thomas Cook failed because of Brexit, trading conditions, and a large debt pile. Although these were contributing factors, there could be a dirtier truth. CDS is insurance against a company going bankrupt. Could the very people who had large vested interests in Thomas cook, the worlds oldest tour company, also be the same ones who bought CDS ‘bets’ on the company failing? Then, with the debt wiped out, CDS holders paid out, and shareholders and staff losing, Thomas Cook naming rights were quietly bought in November last year for JUST £11m. Now, the company is set to relaunch. Make you mind up #thomascook #bankruptcy

We’ve all been told ‘no’ in life many times, and been rejected. Well, in finance, the people saying no (if you’re speaking to VCs particularly), are clueless. I’ve been very vocal about how I think VCs use heard mentality and only care about the direct transparent ‘bottom line’ - what $ they will
Make. Therefore most VCs (not all), will discount your vision, brand, and you and your team to zero, whilst mostly looking at the numbers only, which I think is the wrong way to look at it. Only YOU know (and this applies for everything, not just finance), how you’re going to persevere with your goal and the passion you have to make it work. Wall Street is the only f’ked up place in the world where people take the subway to work to manage the money of people who drive expensive cars - Weirdly ironic isn’t it, and says a lot about the state of financial markets, and why decisions are made for short term gain. That very principal is the reason why you may get rejected but politely tell them to do one. Same for @apple in 1997, they were bailed out by Bill Gates and @microsoft almost out of sympathy, and because Gates was only concerned that Microsoft would be seen to have a monopoly without competition. Granted, they took different paths, but Apple is the bigger and more influential company now, at a time when no one gave them a chance as apparently their visions weren’t ‘commercially viable’. Those people that close doors, will once say they met you, IF you don’t stop to get where you need to be. #financetips #vc #investment

node.text: Are you Struggling right now? Many people are, and that’s totally OK. Think carefully about whom you follow on Instagram, as mental health during these times is more important than ever. What do I mean by positive toxicity? “Get off your ass and learn a skill/language/be the best during these times” - “we are the perfect couple” - “I’m so successful, look at me if you want to be successful” - which could make you feel like you’re failing and not worthy. The truth is, do you. And sure, get motivated by certain people saying this, but remember life isn’t perfect. (I tripped up the stairs writing this - total degenerate). Follow people that keep it real - highs, lows, true emotion. Not everything is perfect, nor should it be. Over and out. #honesty #toxicity #positiveenergy #positivetoxicity

node.text: As many of you know, I used to be an investment banker, so I’ll make a few more little ‘economics’ videos by popular demand (rest in my highlights). Apologies I talk fast here, but the point is, more people are starting to see the indirect effects of policy. In the US alone, a 1% rise in unemployment leads to 40,000 deaths through lower living standards. Last week 30 million people (in America alone!! Think of the rest of the world as well) struggled to put food on the table. However, the divide between Wall Street and Main Street has never been so large. 98% of government stimulus goes to big business and just 2% to small business and individuals who are struggling, which is most people. I’m currently in LA (although took this in Dubai) and so many shops are shuttered with for sale/lease signs. The consumer engine room of the economy is seriously damaged, and if it’s to bounce back, stimulus needs to go to the working population, job creation and small business. Not low interest rates and record high stock markets - that only helps Wall Street and is not a true reflection of the health of the economy #economics #stimuluscheck

It’s a term most of us have heard, but that all of us are now a part of - how? Central Banks.

The ‘original’ Ponzi Scheme was in 1920, and works like a house of cards where people pay money into a product/scheme and filter down that those paying in at the start benefit and the bubble collapses at the bottom, leaving many many people footing the bill.

In 2008, the TARP program in the US saved the likes of AIG, where each US household paid over $4,000 to save big business from failing. Those same big business paid executives and management billions in bonuses for what was poor management.

Now in 2020, the FED and other central banks are printing trillions of dollars that are being pumped into capital markets. Stock markets are trading at all time highs based on valuation multiples of earnings (which have collapsed with demand), but if you look at stock markets you would think the world is as normal. This central bank stimulus is paid for by you and I. The tax payer. Have you seen any direct benefit from this? Didn’t think so. Are you struggling personally? Your small business, household? The reality of unemployment and the actual health of the economy is catastrophic, BUT, big companies are flourishing valuation wise. You’ve paid - they have gained = a modern Ponzi scheme. #ponzischeme #ponzi #stockmarket

node.text: 🇺🇸✈️🇺🇸 American Airlines “Flagship First” seat. Categorically the worst of the 18 long haul first class products currently flying the skies. Complete with plastic cups of course, because of COVID apparently (whilst the plane is 99% full - great logic. #americanair (and before people ask, there was no choice for the route to fly, that’s why I fly this, for work not pleasure, and it’s the ‘best of the rest’ for the routes too seat wise. International it’s poor, for domestic, it works ok.
